          "body": "Verses 5-6 are among the most sobering in the chapter. When Johanan and the military commanders decide to go to Egypt, they do not go alone. They take 'the entire remnant of Judah' — men, women, children, the king's daughters, every person Nebuzaradan had entrusted to Gedaliah's care (43:5-6). The list is exhaustive. Even Jeremiah the prophet and Baruch his scribe are taken — presumably against their will, though the text does not specify. Leadership in disobedience is catastrophically multiplicative. The men who sinned most loudly in verse 2 also sinned most broadly in verses 5-6, carrying an entire community into a trajectory of judgment. This is the social weight of spiritual authority: those who lead God's people bear responsibility not only for their own choices but for every life that follows them. Johanan had been a genuine deliverer once (40:13-16); the same man now leads the remnant into Egypt. Gifted leadership divorced from obedience becomes a larger instrument of destruction than gifted leadership was an instrument of salvation."
