          "title": "The sign-act — stones, throne, and sovereign irony",
          "body": "The sign-act of 43:9-10 is one of Jeremiah's most carefully designed symbolic actions. The prophet is commanded to take large stones and hide them in the mortar of the brick pavement at the entrance to Pharaoh's palace — in full view of the Jews (43:9). The action is public, specific, and geographically precise: the threshold of the very symbol of Egyptian imperial power. Then the oracle interprets it: 'I am going to send Nebuchadnezzar My servant, and I will set his throne right over these stones that I have hidden' (43:10). The sovereign irony is architecturally complete. The remnant had fled to Egypt to escape Babylonian power; the LORD announces that Babylonian power will follow them there and be established on the very ground they fled to. What they buried trying to hide from God's judgment (metaphorically — the act mirrors their concealment of their true motives in ch. 42) becomes the foundation of that judgment's throne. Hendricks' principle applies here: the sign-act is not embellishment — it is the theological argument made visible, performed in stone."
